[We are informed by the communicator that the new case in Hamburg, described above, has now been officially confirmed by the laboratory. Additional EIA cases have been detected in the meantime, in Bavaria; see further. - Mod.AS]

******
[2] 5 new EIA cases, Bavaria
Date: Mon 26 Jun 2017
Source: Pferderevue [in German, trans. submitter SZ, summ., edited]
https://tinyurl.com/y9rb7fga


More cases of new infections with the deadly equine infectious anemia are reported. On [Tue 27 Jun 2017] 5 new cases of the disease became known. In addition to North Rhine-Westphalia, Hamburg and Lower Saxony; Bavaria is now also affected.

Since the occurrence of a disease in a stable in Hagen-Grinden in the district of Verden at the beginning of June [2017], the number of infected horses has increased every week. There are currently 9 horses infected.

As it became known on [Tue 27 Jun 2017], infection was revealed during the serological examination of horses at the equestrian and polo clubs in Dusseldorf. The 1st case of infection had been reported there on [18 Jun 2017]. Now 2 more horses are infected. They have to be killed, because EIA is regarded as incurable. Any attempt of treatment is prohibited.

For the remaining 50 horses of the Poloclub there might be hope. As club president Dirk Baumgärtner told RP online, the first results of their blood tests were all negative.

Further infections are in Bavaria. Recently, an outbreak of equine infectious anemia was officially confirmed in a horse stable in Tagmersheim in the district of Donau-Ries. The 3 animals concerned have to be euthanized. The affected stable is closed for 3 months in accordance with the legal requirements on the Protection against the EIA and a restricted area is established within a radius of 1km [approx 0.6 mi]. In the restricted area, all horse owners must house their animals and contact the veterinary authorities. The horses must be examined clinically and serologically (Coggins test). Healthy animals must be re-tested after 3 months. Only when all horses in the restriction zone are negative in the 2nd test, the restrictions may be lifted.

Outside the restricted area, all private and commercial horse owners in the Donau-Ries region are requested to register their horses with the Veterinary Office Donau-Ries and to report any suspicion indicative of infection with the EIA virus in their horses.

